Morristown Horse Had EEE
------------------------
A horse found dead in the Town of Morristown tested positive for Eastern Equine Encephalitis, (EEE) a deadly, mosquito-borne disease, according to Susan Hathaway, St. Lawrence County public health director. The horse was found in a field on 23 Jul 2012. The positive test result came back Wednesday [25 Jul 2012], Hathaway said.

This death is the 1st horse death from EEE in St. Lawrence County this year. One horse was euthanized after testing positive for the disease last August [2011], and the county also had a case in 2009.

Though EEE has historically stopped in northern Onondaga and Oswego counties, for the most part, rising concern over the disease prompted a vaccination clinic for horses in Heuvelton in June. Hathaway says horses should be vaccinated and contact with mosquitoes should be avoided by removing standing water from your property (mosquitoes breed in standing water) and by wearing appropriate clothing and repellent.

The disease causes a swelling of part of the brain and is often fatal. Last year, a 4-year-old Oswego County girl died from EEE. In a statement, St. Lawrence County Public Health points out mosquitoes carrying both EEE and West Nile disease have been found in the state.

